<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-combinations" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Combinations</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>3.0 Statistics and Probability</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>3.1 Permutations and Combinations</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>Perform combinations involving real life situations</p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>11</p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>40 minutes</p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>10 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>To distinguish between situations where order is important and where it is not.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>Facilitate a discussion on the "Pizza Toppings" vs "Running a Race". If you pick Pepperoni and Mushrooms, is that different from Mushrooms and Pepperoni? This leads to the definition of a combination.</p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <title>The Team Selection</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Suppose you have 4 friends: Alvin (A), Brian (B), Chris (C), and Diana (D).
                <ol>
                    <li>If you need to pick a President and a Secretary, list the possible pairs. (Does order matter?)</li>
                    <li>If you just need to pick a team of 2 to go buy snacks, list the possible pairs. (Does order matter?)</li>
                    <li>Compare your lists. Which one is shorter? Why?</li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <insight>
        <title><p>Combinations: Selecting Without Order</p></title>
        <p>
            A <term>combination</term> is a selection of items from a group where the <strong>order of selection does not matter</strong>. 
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>1. The Relation to Permutations:</strong>
            <line><p>In permutations, choosing A then B is different from B then A. In combinations, these are the same. Therefore, the number of combinations will always be fewer than permutations because we "divide out" the different arrangements of the same group.</p></line>
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>2. The Combination Formula</strong>
            <line><p>To choose <m>r</m> items from <m>n</m> total items, we use the notation <m>_nC_r</m> or <m>\binom{n}{r}</m>:</p></line>
            <me>_nC_r = \frac{n!}{r!(n-r)!}</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>3. Key Difference:</strong>
            <line><p>Notice the extra <m>r!</m> in the denominator? That is what "removes" the extra permutations of the selected items.</p></line>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <example>
      
        <statement>
            <p>1. How many ways can a committee of 3 students be chosen from a class of 10?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Since a committee has no specific roles (order doesn't matter), we use combinations:
                <me>_{10}C_3 = \frac{10!}{3!(10-3)!} = \frac{10!}{3! \times 7!}</me>
                <me>\frac{10 \times 9 \times 8}{3 \times 2 \times 1} = 120 \text{ ways.}</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        
        <statement>
            <p>2. In a small lottery, you choose 4 numbers from 1 to 20. How many different sets of numbers can be chosen?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The order you pick the numbers doesn't change your ticket.
                <me>_{20}C_4 = \frac{20!}{4! 16!} = \frac{20 \times 19 \times 18 \times 17}{4 \times 3 \times 2 \times 1} = 4,845 \text{ sets.}</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        
    
        <statement>
            <p>3. There are 12 people at a meeting. If everyone shakes hands with everyone else exactly once, how many handshakes occur?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                A handshake requires 2 people. The order (Person A shakes Person B's hand) is the same as Person B shaking Person A's.
                <me>_{12}C_2 = \frac{12!}{2! 10!} = \frac{12 \times 11}{2} = 66 \text{ handshakes.}</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        
        <statement>
            <p>4. You want to make a fruit salad using 3 different fruits. You have apples, bananas, grapes, oranges, and pears. How many combinations are possible?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                We have <m>n=5</m> fruits and want to choose <m>r=3</m>.
                <me>_5C_3 = \frac{5!}{3! 2!} = 10 \text{ combinations.}</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        
        <statement>
            <p>5. Show that <m>_nC_r = _nC_{n-r}</m> using <m>_5C_2</m> and <m>_5C_3</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <me>_5C_2 = \frac{5!}{2!3!} = 10</me>
                <me>_5C_3 = \frac{5!}{3!2!} = 10</me>
                Choosing which 2 items to *keep* is the same as choosing which 3 items to *leave out*.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>Calculate <m>_8C_5</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><me>\frac{8!}{5!3!} = \frac{8 \times 7 \times 6}{6} = 56</me></p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>A basketball coach has 12 players but can only start 5. How many different starting lineups can be chosen?</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><me>_{12}C_5 = \frac{12 \times 11 \times 10 \times 9 \times 8}{120} = 792</me></p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>How many ways can you select 2 books from a pile of 9 books to carry during holidays?</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><me>_9C_2 = \frac{9 \times 8}{2} = 36</me></p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>True or False: <m>_nC_n = 1</m>. Justify your answer.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><strong>True.</strong> There is only one way to choose all <m>n</m> items from a group of <m>n</m> items (you just take the whole group).</p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>Identify if the following is a Permutation or Combination: "Selecting 3 students to win identical 10 gift cards."</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><strong>Combination.</strong> Since the gift cards are identical, the order in which the students are picked does not matter.</p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>
        <table>
            <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>Provide a "Checklist" to decide: Order matters? Yes = Permutation. No = Combination.</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>Calculate combinations using the formula and identify them in word problems.</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>Investigate the relationship between combinations and Pascal's Triangle.</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
    </axiom>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-methods.ptx" />

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/reflection.ptx"/>
</section>